se during our team's inquiry and interviews. The major part of the temple was inclined in one direction, which was unexpected, while smaller temples were skewed in a different direction. And everything was discovered to be skewed within the bounds of the temple complex, i.e., within the walls of the temple. According to the villagers and monks, the angle of inclination hasn't changed in the past 40 or 50 years. However, the building's tilt may be caused by a geological factor; perhaps the structure of the earth's crust is uneven. It is impossible to determine whether the inclination is increasing or decreasing. In order to analyze it accurately, as is done in the case of the Leaning Tower of Pisa, some form of measuring mechanism should be provided. Swami Vivekananda International Airport in Raipur (265 km) and Biju Pattnaik International Airport in Bhubaneswar are the closest airports (300 km). The industrial township of Jharsuguda (50 km) is getting a new airport built, and Jamadarpali is the closest airport (10 km). Maneswar is the closest railway station, and it takes 25 kilometers to get to the temple from there. Either Sambalpur City or Maneswar Station are good places to start your journey. Afterward, travel down the Sonpur-Sambalpur Road to Huma Village. The Lord Shiva Leaning Temple can be seen here. Around 25 km separate Sambalpur from the Huma Temple. 5. Samaleswari Temple In Sambalpur, Western Odisha, India, there is a Hindu temple called Samaleswari Temple. It is devoted to the deity known as "Samaleswari," often referred to by the locals as "Mother Samaleswari" or "Samalei Maa." The protector god of Sambalpur, Shree Samaleswari, is a powerful religious figure in the western Indian states of Chhattisgarh and Odisha. The mother goddess Samaleswari, also known as Jagatjanani, Adishakti, Mahalaxmi, and Mahasaraswati, has been worshipped as the creator of the universe on the banks of the river Mahanadi from ancient times. She is the sole Goddess in Odisha, 